<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-cleanup-undeposited-funds-operator">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Who fixes it</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">A Certified ProAdvisor clears the pileup and reconciles behind it.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Forcing the balance to zero is easy and wrong &mdash; deleting payments destroys the link to the invoices and the bank and usually makes reconciliation worse. The work that actually restores trust in the numbers is everything around the pileup: separating the genuinely uncleared payments from the duplicates, grouping the real ones into deposits that match the bank, removing the double-counted deposits after a backup, and re-running reconciliation until each affected month ties to the statement again. A Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor with active Online and Desktop certifications does that against a written scope and confirms income is no longer overstated before closing. If the correction changes income for a period you&rsquo;ve already filed on, that&rsquo;s a question for your CPA &mdash; we fix the books and hand off a CPA-ready file; we don&rsquo;t file taxes. Independent firm &mdash; not Intuit, and not Intuit&rsquo;s software support; an Intuit account, login, or billing matter stays with Intuit.</p>
